---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Teacher Area" mode="teacher" active="teacher-home" description="Teacher area for the Macbeth coursework unit: scheme of work, lesson sequences and assessment guidance for the Edexcel International GCSE Literary Heritage essay.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">For teachers</p>
      <h1>Teaching the Macbeth coursework</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        Everything on the student site, organised for the classroom: a five-lesson scheme built
        around the Literary Heritage coursework essay, lesson-by-lesson detail with the activities
        and pitfalls, and assessment guidance for the Edexcel International GCSE (4ET1) Component 3.
        The unit assumes the play was read and studied the previous term.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="grid cols-3">
        <a class="card" href="/teachers/scheme-of-work/">
          <span class="num">Plan</span>
          <h3>Scheme of work</h3>
          <p>The five coursework lessons mapped in one table: focus, key content, student outcome and the site pages that support each lesson.</p>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="/teachers/lessons/">
          <span class="num">Teach</span>
          <h3>Lessons in detail</h3>
          <p>Learning objectives, activity sequences, the pitfalls to pre-empt and the written outcome for each of the five lessons.</p>
        </a>
        <a class="card" href="/teachers/assessment/">
          <span class="num">Assess</span>
          <h3>Assessment</h3>
          <p>The AO1, AO2 and AO4 split in practical terms, a paraphrased quality ladder, the comment-only marking workflow and the examiner pitfalls.</p>
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="grid cols-2" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
        <div class="box" style="margin:0;">
          <h3>How the two sites fit together</h3>
          <p>
            The student site follows the play and funnels towards the
            <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>: every guide ends by pointing students back to
            the essay, and the material they need for it is laid out across
            <a href="/guide/">the guide</a>, <a href="/themes/">themes</a>,
            <a href="/characters/">characters</a>, <a href="/context/">context</a> and the
            <a href="/quotations/">quotation bank</a>. Use the scene guides for pre-reading, catch-up or
            revision; use the lesson sequences here for classroom teaching. Students who miss a lesson can
            recover the ground on their own.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="box teach" style="margin:0;">
          <h3>Why there is no AI feedback tool on this site</h3>
          <p>
            Other sites in the Extended English family carry an AI marking desk. This one deliberately does
            not, because the Macbeth essay is assessed coursework (NEA), and the integrity rules govern how
            it may be helped. The candidate signs to declare the work is their own and to reference any
            sources and any artificial intelligence tools used; the teacher signs to declare the work was
            completed without unacceptable assistance and that AI has not been used to mark it.
          </p>
          <p>
            An automated feedback tool would sit on the wrong side of both declarations, so we left it out by
            design. The decision was made to keep the signed declarations honest and the assessed piece
            entirely the student&rsquo;s: the site teaches the play and the process, but the argument and the
            writing stay theirs. The <a href="/coursework/#integrity">integrity rules</a> are set out for
            students in plain language, with the reasoning and not just the prohibition.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="box" style="max-width: 46rem; margin-top: 2.5rem;">
        <h3>A note on copyright and privacy</h3>
        <p>
          The site quotes the play only in short extracts for criticism and review, and every quotation is
          verified before use and cited by act and scene. All summaries and commentary are original; nothing
          from the specification, the published mark scheme or Pearson training materials is reproduced.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
